        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For most active men over 40, 150g is within the evidence-based range. Research supports 1.2–1.6g per kilogram of bodyweight for muscle preservation and recomposition. For a 165–190 pound man training consistently, 150g sits comfortably within that range and is not considered excessive."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How is 150g of protein different from 130g?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The difference is roughly 20g — about one additional high-protein serving per day. A man hitting 130g consistently can reach 150g by adding a cup of cottage cheese, a protein shake, or slightly larger dinner portions. It doesn't require restructuring meals, just one deliberate addition."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Where does 150g of protein fit in the daily protein range?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "150g sits between the 130g maintenance target and the 160g recomposition target. It's the right level for men who are consistently hitting 130g and want to push toward active body recomposition — losing fat while maintaining or building muscle — without jumping straight to the more demanding 160g target."
        }
      },
