    <h2>Getting From 130g to 150g: The Two Changes</h2>

    <p>If you're already hitting 130g, the move to 150g requires exactly two things — not a new diet, not more meals.</p>

    <table class="food-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Change</th>
          <th>What to Do</th>
          <th>Protein Added</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Add an afternoon snack</td>
          <td>1 cup cottage cheese or 1 scoop whey</td>
          <td class="protein-col">+25g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Increase dinner portion</td>
          <td>5oz → 7oz beef or salmon</td>
          <td class="protein-col">+14g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Slightly larger lunch</td>
          <td>5oz → 7oz chicken breast</td>
          <td class="protein-col">+13g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Add Greek yogurt to breakfast</td>
          <td>If not already included</td>
          <td class="protein-col">+17–20g</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Pick any combination that adds up to roughly 20g. That's the entire upgrade from 130g to 150g. If you haven't built the 130g habit yet, start there — see <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-130g-protein-looks-like/">what 130 grams of protein looks like</a> first. And the foundation for all of this is <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">understanding what 120 grams of protein looks like</a> in a real day.</p>

    <h2>Why 150g Is a Different Kind of Target Than 120g or 130g</h2>

    <p>At 120g and 130g, protein is doing defensive work — preventing muscle loss, slowing the effects of anabolic resistance, maintaining what you've built. That's meaningful and worth doing.</p>

    <p>At 150g, protein starts doing offensive work. Combined with consistent resistance training, 150g gives your muscles enough raw material to not just maintain but to respond to training with actual growth. The research on body recomposition in men over 40 consistently points to this range — 1.5–1.6g per kilogram of bodyweight — as the threshold where the equation shifts from preservation to rebuilding.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>The math for a 185-pound man:</strong> 185 lbs ÷ 2.2 = 84kg. At 1.5g/kg that's 126g. At 1.8g/kg that's 151g. For an active man at this weight, 150g sits right at the upper end of the maintenance range and the lower end of active recomposition. It's the productive middle ground.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Tracking Matters More as the Number Gets Higher</h2>

    <p>At 100g, a rough estimate gets you close enough. At 120g, feel starts to work for men who eat consistently. At 150g, you need to actually know your number — because the margin between thinking you hit 150g and actually hitting it is wide enough to matter.</p>

    <p>The habit that makes 150g consistent isn't eating more — it's knowing your running total by mid-afternoon. If you're at 80g by 2pm, you know exactly what the afternoon snack and dinner need to do. If you're at 105g, you have flexibility. That visibility is the difference between hitting 150g most days and hitting it occasionally.</p>

